		<div class="jobs">
			<section class="job">
				<div class="job-header">
					<span class="job-title">Front-End Developer</span>
					<i class="job-icon">✕</i>
				</div>

				<div class="job-body">
					<p>We are a small team where each individual member works on many different projects and has a hand in the direction of the product.</p>

					<p>This position leans more to the javascript development side of front end development. You will be working on our “mid end” — the area between HTML/CSS templates and back-end API.</p>

					<p>Some key relevant technical challenges and areas of focus:<br>
					- New tab extension context requiring fast page rendering<br>
					- Building out the product offering and surrounding infrastructure<br>
					- Taking product vision and templates and executing them</p>


					<h4>You Are</h4>

					<p>
					- A developer with 2+ years of industry experience or equivalent.<br>
					- Academically educated or self-taught with a strong grasp of computer science fundamentals.<br>
					- Detail oriented and aware of edge cases when designing, building, and debugging.<br>
					- Pragmatic and able to make good decisions among tradeoffs of speed and quality.<br>
					- Passionate about working on something you find meaningful and resonate with the Momentum vision.</p>


					<h4>Helpful Experience</h4>

					<p>
					- Strong experience building web-based javascript applications.<br>
					- Firm grasp of HTML and CSS.<br>
					- Experience with Backbone, Node, Express, Vue.<br>
					- Experience in a startup, SaaS, or other entrepreneurial pursuit.<br>
					- A demonstrated passion for software such as a history of side projects/product creation.<br>
					- Up to date with industry practices (agile, source control, APIs, security).<br>
					- Appreciative of well designed products and user experience.</p>


					<h4>How to Apply</h4>

					<p>If this opportunity excites you, send your resume and work examples (Github profile accepted) to <a href="mailto:join@momentumdash.com">join@momentumdash.com</a>. We look forward to meeting you!</p>

				</div>
			</section>
			<section class="job">
				<div class="job-header">
					<span class="job-title">Full-Stack Developer</span>
					<i class="job-icon">✕</i>
				</div>

				<div class="job-body">
					<p>We are a small team where each individual member works on many different projects and has a hand in the direction of the product.</p>

					<p>Some of our key technical challenges and areas of focus:<br>
					- New tab extension context requiring fast page rendering.<br>
					- Scaling an API to 50M API hits/day.<br>
					- Free/Plus version delivery in same package<br>
					- Building out the product offering and surrounding infrastructure
					</p>


					<h4>You Are</h4>

					<p>
					- A developer with 2+ years of industry experience.<br>
					- Academically educated or self-taught with a strong grasp of computer science fundamentals.<br>
					- Detail oriented and aware of edge cases when designing, building, and debugging.<br>
					- Pragmatic and able to make good decisions among tradeoffs of speed and quality.<br>
					- Appreciative of well designed products and user experience.<br>
					- Passionate about working on something you find meaningful and resonate with the Momentum vision.</p>


					<h4>Helpful Experience</h4>

					<p>
					- Experience building web-based javascript applications.<br>
					- Experience with Javascript, Backbone, Node, Vue, C#.<br>
					- A particular specialty whether front-end, back-end, platform (Azure), or mobile.<br>
					- Experience in a startup, SaaS, or other entrepreneurial pursuit.<br>
					- A demonstrated passion for software such as a history of side projects/product creation.<br>
					- Up to date with industry practices (agile, source control, APIs, security).</p>


					<h4>How to Apply</h4>

					<p>If this opportunity excites you, send your resume and work examples (Github profile accepted) to <a href="mailto:join@momentumdash.com">join@momentumdash.com</a>. We look forward to meeting you!</p>

				</div>
